{
  "answer": "**Morning purification** for a Brahmin householder (*gṛhastha*) centers on rising at the Brahma-muhūrta (roughly 96 minutes before sunrise), performing evacuation, and purifying (*śauca*) with water and earth.[^1][^2]\n\nIn *Manusmṛti*, the routine begins with awakening in Brahma-muhūrta to contemplate Dharma before evacuation; one must avoid discharging urine or feces in forbidden places (e.g., water, ploughed land, facing wind/fire/sun), cover the ground first (with wood, clod, grass, etc.), and purify with water afterward, facing north by day.[^3] Morning twilight (*prātarsandhyā*) requires standing to recite the *Sāvitrī* until sunrise.[^4]\n\n*Viṣṇu Smṛti* echoes rising at Brahma-muhūrta for evacuation (facing north by day/south at night/twilights as day), with the same prohibitions on places.[^5] It adds precise counts of earth lumps for *śauca*: one on the penis, three on the anus, ten on one hand, seven on both hands, three on the feet (doubled for students, tripled for forest-dwellers, quadrupled for ascetics).[^6]\n\n*Viṣṇu* thus elaborates the mechanical steps of post-evacuation *śauca*—absent as specifics in *Manu*—tailoring purification to one's *āśrama* while confirming *Manu*'s directional and situational rules.\n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 4](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/04/translation/#p-e69207).\n\n[^2]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, [Chapter 60](/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/60/translation/#p-d04dc6).\n\n[^3]: *Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 4](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/04/translation/#p-fe84fd) (evacuation rules); [/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/04/translation/#p-133ce4] (Brahma-muhūrta).\n\n[^4]: *Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 2](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-133cc6).\n\n[^5]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, [Chapter 60](/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/60/translation/#p-ea086d).\n\n[^6]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, [Chapter 60](/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/60/translation/#p-5e91b7).",
